The horizontal discretisation is on an orthogonal curvilinear grid nominally one degree for both longitude and latitude. It has the following refinements: (1) a tripolar grid (Murray 1996) is used north of 65°N to preclude a singularity at the geographical north pole; (2) a cosine dependent (Mercator) grid is used south of 30°S to avoid large grid cell aspect ratios and also to better resolve zonal currents in the Southern Ocean and at the Antarctic margin; and, (3) a refinement of latitudinal spacing to 1/3° is applied between 10°S and 10°N to better resolve predominantly zonal equatorial ocean currents.

The size of data that is being considered for processing is probably the most important factor. If the data can fit into the system memory, then clusters are usually not required and the entire data can be processed on a single machine. The platforms such as GPU, Multicore CPUs etc. can be used to speed up the data processing in this case. If the data does not fit into the system memory, then one has to look at other cluster options such as Hadoop, Spark etc. Again, Hadoop and Spark clusters can handle large amount of data but Hadoop has well developed tools and frameworks although it is slower for iterative tasks. The user has to decide if he needs to use off-the-shelf tools which are available for Hadoop or if he wants to optimize the cluster performance in which case Spark is more appropriate

description: FLOPs (Floating Point Operations) is a measure of computational performance, and PetaFLOPs represents one quadrillion (10^15) floating-point operations per second. In the context of language models like GPT-3, pretraining involves a significant amount of computation to train the model on a large corpus of text data, and the "PF-days" metric quantifies the total computational power used for pretraining, typically measured in PetaFLOPs multiplied by the number of days the computation took.

label: carbon emitted (tCO2eq)
description: measured in "metric tons of carbon dioxide equivalent." It is a unit of measurement used to express the amount of greenhouse gas emissions produced by human activities, such as burning fossil fuels, industrial processes, deforestation, agriculture, and recently training large-scale generative AI models. The term "equivalent" is used because different greenhouse gases have varying global warming potentials (GWP), meaning they trap different amounts of heat in the atmosphere over specific time frames.  Carbon dioxide (CO2) is the most common greenhouse gas emitted by human activities, but there are other greenhouse gases like methane (CH4) and nitrous oxide (N2O), which are more potent in terms of their heat-trapping ability compared to CO2. When calculating the total greenhouse gas emissions, the contributions of different gases are converted into a common unit of measurement, which is the metric ton of carbon dioxide equivalent (tCO2eq), to provide a standardized and comparable value for the total impact on climate change.  By using tCO2eq, it becomes easier to understand the overall environmental impact of various activities and implement strategies to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to mitigate climate change.

description:
Death - The total and/or new number of fatalities caused by COVID-19.
Active/new cases - Includes total confirmed cases and/or active/new cases, which may or may not include hospitalized patients. Critical and severe cases are considered separately as ancillary indicators.
Recovered - Patients who have recovered from the infection
Tests - Negative/positive and/or total tests carried out on suspected patients.

ICU.
Tests - Tests, test types, and any test result (positive or negative).
Demographic data - Case identification data (e.g., age, sex, race, ethnicity, nationality).
Geographic data - Any kind of data related to locations and population (e.g., city/state/region details, distance data, GIS data).
Population data - Any population-related data (e.g., population demographics, travels data, occupational
data).
Hospitalized - Any case infected with COVID-19 hosted in the hospital to receive clinical care.

label: Research Object
description:
Architecture Analysis Method
A method for analyzing existing software architectures, e.g., to measure or evaluate specific qualities or functions.

Architecture Design Method
A method for designing software architectures, e.g., to obtain specific qualities or functions.

Architecture Optimization Method
A method to optimize existing architectures (implemented or designed) to regarding specific qualities or properties.

Architecture Evolution
The  process  of  maintaining  and adapting  existing  software architecture to meet requirement and environmental changes [Imran et al., 2016]. This includes papers that investigate the evolution of specific architectures.

Architecture Description Language
A formal or software language to create a description of a software architecture, i.e., "any form of expression for use in architecture descriptions" [ISO/IEC 42010].

Architecture Decision Making
In software development and evolution, decision-making is an integral part. Thus, various decisions are being made throughout the software development life cycle concerning processes, products, tools, methods, and techniques. From a decision-making perspective, all these questions are confronted by different objectives and constraints, a huge number of variables under dynamically  changing  requirements,  processes,  actors,  stakeholders,  tools  and  techniques. This is combined with incomplete, fuzzy or inconsistent information about all the involved artefacts. [Ruhe2003]

A description of an architecture (e.g. domain-specific or to solve recurring problems) that can be tailored to specific use cases.

Architecture Pattern
An architectural pattern is a general, reusable solution to a commonly occurring problem in software architecture within a given context. Patterns with negative effects on the product, i.e., anti-patterns, are also included here. [Taylor et al, 2009]

Architecture Description
An Architecture Description (AD) is a work product used to express the Architecture of some System Of Interest. An AD describes one possible Architecture for a System Of Interest. An AD may take the form of a document, a set of models, a model repository, or some other form [ISO/IEC 42010].

Architectural Aspects
A method for identifying or specifying specific architectural aspects in existing implemented architectures, e.g., automatically identifying transactional contexts in an architecture. Note that if you analyse an architecture description containing these aspects, the analysis is a separate research object.

Technical Debt
"In software-intensive systems, technical debt consists of design or implementation constructs that are expedient in the short term, but set up a technical context that can make a future change more costly or impossible. Technical debt is a contingent liability whose impact is limited to internal system qualities, primarily maintainability and evolvability." [Avgeriou2016]

Architecture Extraction
Designing and realizing methods and algorithms to automatically extract architecture information from existing implementations.

Architectural Assumptions
Assumptions are the reasons for architectural decisions that are more or less arbitrarily taken on the fly because of personal experience, background, domain knowledge, the artifacts reused, and the like [Lago et al., 2005]

The paper begins with an overview of the development theory and policy debates on the commodity-based development model and the implementation of indigenous rights. Finally, the question of whether sustainable practices of indigenous groups should be understood as an expression of their specific culture and whether these types of economic activity are relevant and realisable as models for a larger social context will be explored.

The relationship between resource-based developments and the implementation of indigenous autonomy rights has hardly been analysed to date. Numerous studies in the research field emphasise the importance of the recognition of indigenous rights for processes of social decolonisation and democratisation and identify their guarantee as a central prerequisite for the protection of ecologically sensitive regions (e.g. Bebbington et al. 2018). protection of ecologically sensitive regions. However, they often tend to focus indigenous groups in conflicts over land and resources on the defence of "traditional ways of life" and a "harmonious relationship with nature" and thus run the risk of ignoring important objectives which, in addition to the defence of land and raw materials, can also include coping with social change and improving the general living conditions of the affected population groups.

label: context length (in tokens)

This property is a key process parameter that influences the material properties and the quality of the manufactured parts.

It is a crucial parameter that impacts the interfacial characterization and mechanical properties of functionally graded materials, such as the 316L/CuCrZr material studied in this research paper. By examining the hatch distance, researchers can optimize process parameters to enhance the properties of the fabricated parts.

label: Volumetric Energy Density [J/mm³]

description: This predicate indicates that the research paper involves or focuses on a specific instance of a Vision-Language Model (VLM), such as Llava. It highlights the use or development of a particular VLM as a key aspect of the paper's contribution, emphasizing the model's role in the research within the field of vision and language processing.

label: Data assimilation technique
description: Data assimilation technique refers to the method or process used to integrate observational data into a computational model to improve its accuracy and predictive capability. This technique is crucial in fields such as meteorology, oceanography, and environmental science, where it helps to combine real-world measurements with model simulations to produce more reliable and precise results. Describing this property in a research paper highlights the specific approach or algorithm employed to assimilate data, which can be a significant contribution to advancing modeling and forecasting methodologies.

label: Assimilated model
description: Assimilated model refers to a computational or mathematical model that has been improved or refined by integrating observational data through data assimilation techniques. This property highlights the use of data assimilation to enhance model accuracy and reliability in the research.

label: state variables updated
description: This property describes the specific state variables within a system or model that are updated as part of the research contribution. It highlights which variables' values are changed or evolved during the process or experiment, indicating the dynamic aspects addressed by the study.

label: purpose of assimilation
description: The 'purpose of assimilation' predicate captures the main goal or objective behind the process of assimilation discussed in a research paper. It describes why assimilation is performed or studied, highlighting the intended outcomes, motivations, or aims that drive the assimilation process within the context of the research. This property helps clarify the contribution of the paper by specifying the targeted purpose or rationale for assimilation.

label: assimilation window
description: Assimilation window refers to the specific time period during which observational data is integrated into a model or system to improve its accuracy and predictive capability. It is a critical parameter in data assimilation processes, determining the temporal scope for incorporating new information to update model states or forecasts.

label: Attitude toward Sustainability
description: Attitude toward Sustainability refers to the stance, perspective, or approach that individuals, organizations, or societies hold regarding sustainable practices and principles. This property captures how the research addresses, influences, or reflects concerns, values, and commitments related to sustainability, including environmental, social, and economic dimensions. It is used to describe the contribution of the research in promoting, analyzing, or critiquing sustainable development and responsible resource management.

label: research artifact
description: The 'research artifact' predicate refers to any tangible or digital object created or used during the research process that embodies the main contribution of the paper. This can include datasets, software, algorithms, models, experimental setups, or any other material that supports the research findings and enables reproducibility and further exploration.

label: research components
description: Research components refer to the key elements or parts of a research study that collectively contribute to the overall research contribution. These components include the theory type, emphasis, formal concepts, independed variables etc. Identifying and describing these components helps in understanding the structure and significance of the research work.

label: focus and intent
description: Focus and intent refer to the primary aim or objective that the research paper seeks to address or achieve. This property captures the central theme, goal of the paper, or motivation that guide the study, highlighting what the authors intend to investigate, demonstrate, or contribute to their field and they outcome of this research.

label: paper goal
description: The 'paper goal' predicate captures the primary objective or aim that the research paper seeks to achieve. It succinctly describes the main purpose or intended outcome of the study, highlighting what the authors set out to investigate, develop, or demonstrate. This property is essential for understanding the core contribution and focus of the research work.

label: hydropower scheme type
description: Hydropower scheme type refers to the classification or category of a hydropower project based on its design, operation, and technology used. This property helps to specify the nature of the hydropower system studied or proposed in the research, such as run-of-river, reservoir-based, pumped storage, or tidal power schemes. Identifying the hydropower scheme type is crucial for understanding the research contribution related to energy generation methods, environmental impact, efficiency, and technological innovation in hydropower development.

label: power plant scale
description: Power plant scale refers to the size or capacity of a power generation facility, typically measured in terms of its output capacity (e.g., megawatts). This property is important for characterizing the scope and impact of research related to power plants, including their design, efficiency, environmental impact, and economic feasibility.

label: power plant type
description: The 'power plant type' predicate specifies the category or classification of a power generation facility discussed or analyzed in the research. This property helps to identify the specific kind of power plant (e.g., coal-fired, nuclear, hydroelectric, solar, wind) that is the focus of the study, enabling a clear understanding of the technological or methodological contributions related to that type of power generation.

label: flow duration curve
description: A flow duration curve (FDC) is a graphical representation used in hydrology to show the percentage of time that flow in a stream or river is likely to equal or exceed a certain value. It is a cumulative frequency curve that helps characterize the variability and availability of water flow over a specified period. The FDC is useful for water resource management, ecological studies, and engineering design, providing insights into flow regimes, drought conditions, and flood risks.
